<h1>Problem 2118 - 2021 Christmas Mock, P2 of 6</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 7</h2>
<p>Find all functions \(f \colon \mathbb{R}_{> 0} \to \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0}\) satisfying \[\big(f(x)+f(y)\big)^3=xf(x)+yf(y)+3f(xy)\big(f(x)+f(y)\big)\] for all positive real numbers \(x\) and \(y\).</p>
<h2>Thinking</h2>
<div class=skib>
<p>The \(\mathbb{R}_{> 0} \to \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0}\) condition is very interesting. Suppose there is some \(k\) such that \(f(k) = 0\). Then, we get
\[f(x)^3 = xf(x) + 3f(xy)f(x)\]
Suppose \(f(x) \neq 0\), in which case we get \(f(x)^2 = x + 3f(xy)\), and taking \(x = 1\), we get \(f(1) = 1\). So if there exists \(k\) such that \(f(k) = 0\), then \(f(1) = 0\) or \(1\). Let's try to directly get \(f(1)\):
\[8f(1)^3 = 2f(1) + 6f(1)^2 \implies f(1) = 0 \text{ or } 1\]
If \(f(1) = 0\), then \(f(x)^3 = xf(x) + 3f(x)^2\) for all \(x\). So either \(f(x) = 0\), or \(f(x) = \frac{3 + \sqrt{9+ 4x}}{2}\). <br>
If \(f(1) = 1\), then \((f(x) + 1)^3  = xf(x) + 1 + 3f(x)(f(x) + 1) \implies xf(x) = f(x)^3\). So either \(f(x) = 0\) or \(f(x) = \sqrt{x}\).</p>
<p>Before we plug in these weird functions, let us try \((x, x)\)
\[8f(x)^3 = 2xf(x) + 3f(x^2) 2f(x) \implies f(x) = 0 \;\; \text{or} \;\; 8f(x)^2 = 2x + 6f(x^2)\]
Using \(f(x) =  \frac{3 + \sqrt{9+ 4x}}{2}\), we get
\[9 + 2x + 4 \sqrt{9 + 4x} = \sqrt{9+ 4x^2}\]
This is literally impossible for \(x > 0\), so \(f(x) = 0\) for all \(x\) if \(f(1) = 0\), which is a working solution.</p>
<p>Now suppose \(f(1) = 1\), and \(f(x) = \sqrt{x}\), \(f(y) = \sqrt{y}\). 
\[(\sqrt{x} + \sqrt{y})^3 = x\sqrt{x} + y\sqrt{y} + 3f(xy)(\sqrt{x} + \sqrt{y}) \implies f(xy) = \sqrt{xy}\]
Suppose \(f(x) = \sqrt{x}\), \(f(y) = 0\).
\[(\sqrt{x})^3 = x\sqrt{x} + 3f(xy)\sqrt{x} \implies f(xy) = 0\]
This is very interesting. Let us think about powers of \(y\) where \(f(y) = 0\) - note first that \(f(y^2)\) can be \(0\) or \(y\) without any immediate contradiction, so suppose \(f(y^2) = y\). This means \(f(y^3) = 0\), \(f(y^4) = y^2\), and so on. Ah, this doesn't really give us anything - if we take \(f(y^n)\) to be the first \(n\) such that this value is \(0\), we just get something about multiple of \(n\) powers. </p>
<p>Actually bruh wait what's wrong with a function like: \(f(x) = \sqrt{x}\) for \(x \in \{\dots, a^{-3}, a^{-2}, a^{-1}, 1, a, a^2, a^3, \dots\}\), and \(f(x) = 0\) otherwise? Literally nothing because it's closed under multiplication and inverses. This is so troll XD. Basically if any multiplicative 'group' generated by some set gets sent to \(\sqrt{x}\) and everything else gets sent to \(0\), that works (in fact, I didn't notice before but \(f(1) = 1\) and everything else \(0\) also works) and are the only solutions due to multiplicative closure and inverse existence.</p>
</div>
